{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480821"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:52:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:52:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"114"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/114"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.3,0.09,0.4,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"114"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46566"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/114"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"114"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31482"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"182"},{"type":"tags","id":"2028"},{"type":"tags","id":"6610"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7307"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13870"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46566"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman develops a painful, swollen left leg two weeks after the birth of her first child. She is breastfeeding the infant. Her medical history includes polycystic renal disease and her serum creatinine 4 weeks ago was 250 umol/L (40 - 85). The only medication she is using is salbutamol for asthma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 136/85 mmHg, respiratory rate of 14/min, and temperature 36.8C. Apart from her tender erythematous oedematous calf, the rest of the physical examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA duplex doppler study shows clot in the deep venous system of the calf, with extension into the thigh.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alteplase","Apixaban","Dabigatran","Warfarin","Rivaroxaban"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question focuses on the management of proximal DVT in two special circumstances; breast feeding and renal impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn important consideration is breast-feeding. \u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E does not pass into breastmilk as it is highly protein bound and thus is safe for this patient.\u00a0Low molecular weight heparin such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eenoxaparin\u003C/strong\u003E is transferred into breast milk, as are \u003Cstrong\u003Edirect-acting oral anticoagulants (DOACs)\u003C/strong\u003E. Hence, of the options provided, \u003Cstrong\u003Ewarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is the best choice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn important consideration is renal impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin \u003C/strong\u003Eis hepatically cleared and thus is suitable for patients with renal impairment. The anticoagulant effect takes a number of days to begin working and thus treatment for an established DVT should include warfarin given with enoxaparin (low molecular weight heparin) to provide immediate anticoagulation while awaiting the therapeutic effect of warfarin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll three of the \u003Cstrong\u003Edirect-acting oral anticoagulants (DOACs)\u003C/strong\u003E are renally cleared and should be avoided in patients with advanced renal impairment/chronic kidney disease. The creatinine clearance is used to make this decision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlteplase\u003C/strong\u003E is a strong thrombolytic agent reserved for large pulmonary embolism treatment, STEMI treatment where percutaneous coronary intervention is not available and for some ischaemic strokes; it is not indicated for DVT treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf there was any urgency for the need for anticoagulation, a heparin bridge could be considered. However, a delay of 24 - 36 hours waiting for the therapeutic effects of warfarin is unlikely to be of any significant consequence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Warfarin should be considered the anticoagulant of choice in patients with advanced renal impairment.","Warfarin is the anticoagulant of choice for patients actively breastfeeding as it does not pass into the breast milk."],"references":["Ageno, W, Gallus, AS, Wittkowsky, A, Crowther, M, Hylek, EM \u0026 Palareti, G 2012, \u2018Anti-coagulant therapy\u2019,\u00a0Chest, vol. 141, no. 2, pp. 44-88.","Fick-Brosnahan, GM, Belz, MM, McFann, KK, Johnson, AM \u0026 Schrier, RW 2002, \u2018Relationship between renal volume growth and renal function in autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease: A longitudinal study\u2019,\u00a0American Journal of Kidney Disease,\u00a0vol. 39, no. 6, pp. 1127-34.","Hotham, N \u0026 Hotham, E 2015, \u2018Drugs in breastfeeding\u2019,\u00a0Australian Prescriber, vol. 38, pp. 156-9.","Nickson, C 2019,\u00a0Altephase (rtPA),\u00a0Life in the Fast Lane, viewed 20/08/2020, \u003Chttps://litfl.com/alteplase-rt-pa/\u003E."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31482"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"114"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31482"},"